{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598268"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15452"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15452"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.04,0.14,0.14,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8143"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61868"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8143"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47314"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19943"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61868"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe two main types of inflammatory bowel disease are ulcerative colitis and Crohn\u0027s disease. Each has its own characteristic pattern of gut involvement and distinct pathological features. Both of these help in establishing the diagnosis and differentiating between the two.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features occurs in Crohn\u0027s disease but not ulcerative colitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Skip lesions","Mucosal inflammation","Crypt abscesses","Pseudopolyps","Bloody diarrhoea"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key distinguishing features between Crohn\u0027s disease and ulcerative colitis include pattern and depth of inflammation. \u003Cstrong\u003ESkip lesions\u003C/strong\u003E are a hallmark of Crohn\u0027s disease, where areas of inflammation are interspersed with normal mucosa. In contrast, ulcerative colitis shows continuous inflammation from the rectum proximally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMucosal inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecrypt abscesses\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudopolyps\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in both conditions. \u003Cstrong\u003EBloody diarrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of ulcerative colitis but can also occur in Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther features specific to Crohn\u0027s disease include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransmural inflammation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGranulomas\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotential involvement of any part of the gastrointestinal tract\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFistula formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Crohn\u0027s disease is characterised by transmural inflammation and skip lesions, while ulcerative colitis shows continuous mucosal inflammation.","Crohn\u0027s disease can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus, while ulcerative colitis only affects the colon.","Granulomas are a histological feature specific to Crohn\u0027s disease."],"references":["Cai Z, Wang S, Li J. Treatment of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Comprehensive Review. Front Med (Lausanne). 2021 Dec 20;8:765474. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2021.765474. PMID: 34988090; PMCID: PMC8720971","McDowell C, Farooq U, Haseeb M. Inflammatory Bowel Disease. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262182","Fakhoury M, Negrulj R, Mooranian A, Al-Salami H. Inflammatory bowel disease: clinical aspects and treatments. J Inflamm Res. 2014 Jun 23;7:113-20. doi: 10.2147/JIR.S65979. PMID: 25075198; PMCID: PMC4106026","Tavakoli P, Vollmer-Conna U, Hadzi-Pavlovic D, Grimm MC. A Review of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Model of Microbial, Immune and Neuropsychological Integration. Public Health Rev. 2021 May 5;42:1603990. doi: 10.3389/phrs.2021.1603990. PMID: 34692176; PMCID: PMC8386758","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47314"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15452"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47314"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T16:46:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T16:46:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8143"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61868"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name"